<%= content_for :heading do %>
  <h1>Typography</h1>
  <p>Sage provides a constrained, purposeful set of typographic styles. These styles map as much as possible to functional roles so you know when each can be used.</p>
<% end %>
<%= content_for :quick_links do %>
  <div class="quick-links">
    <h2 class="quick-links__title">Contents</h2>
    <ul class="quick-links__body">
      <li class="quick-links__item">
        <a href="#guidance" class="quick-links__link">Guidance</a>
      </li>
      <li class="quick-links__item">
        <a href="#spec-table" class="quick-links__link">Type Spec Reference</a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
<% end %>
<div class="sage-type">
  <p>
    The Sage type system uses a major second modular scale (factor of 1.125) with a base font size of 16px.
  </p>
  <p>
    Typography in our system uses <code>t-sage-</code> classes in order to apply a given typographical specification to an element
    These can be used on any element to apply the desired typographical styles regardless of the tag. This allows a
    wide range of flexibility for applying a desired style to an element while still using the most semantic element possible
    for a given context.
  </p>
  <p>
    Setting individual styles manually should be avoided, but where needed, should be sure to use the appropriate
    <%= link_to "design tokens", pages_foundations_path(:token) %>.
    In the end, we prefer adding new entries to the type spec over including one-off styling.
  </p>
  <h2 id="spec-table">Type Spec Reference</h2>
  <table class="sage-specs">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Style</th>
        <th>Class</th>
        <th>Weight</th>
        <th>Size</th>
        <th>Line-height</th>
        <th>Kerning</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
