      </tr>
    </tbody>
    <tfoot>
      <tr>
        <td colspan="6">
          <p class="t-sage-body-xsmall">
            * The <code>t-sage-body{-size}</code> classes also have weight variations:
               append <code>-med</code> for <span class="t-sage-body-xsmall-med">medium (500)</span>;
               append <code>-semi</code> for <span class="t-sage-body-xsmall-semi">semibold (600)</span>;
               append <code>-bold</code> for <span class="t-sage-body-xsmall-bold">bold (700)</span>
           </p>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tfoot>
  </table>

  <p>
    The type specs above map logically to corresponding HTML elements, as well as the following:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <span class="t-sage-body">Body</span> is used as the default type style, and is thus applied to elements such as
      <code>li</code>, <code>dd</code>, <code>td</code>, <code>blockquote</code>, and more.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Body Bold</strong> is used for elements that are typically bolded such as
      <code>tr</code>, <code>dt</code>, <code>strong</code>, and <code>b</code>.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    As an example, see here how the "Heading 3" type spec can be applied to an
    <code>h3</code> element:
  </p>

  <div class="docs-container">
    <div class="sage-type">
      <h3 class="t-sage-heading-3">Lorem ipsum dolor sit</h3>
      <div class="sage-code-snippet">
        <pre class="prettyprint"><code>&lt;h3 class="t-sage-heading-3"&gt;Lorem ipsum dolor sit&lt;/h3&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    But the exact specs can also be applied to any element such as a <code>span</code>.
    This is not meant to be an excuse for using non-semantic markup, but rather,
    to free a spec to be applied to the most semantic element in context regardless
    of the spec's name.
  </p>

  <div class="docs-container">
    <div class="sage-type">
      <span class="t-sage-heading-3">Lorem ipsum dolor sit</span>
      <div class="sage-code-snippet">
        <pre class="prettyprint"><code>&lt;span class="t-sage-heading-3"&gt;Lorem ipsum dolor sit&lt;/span&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    For setting text in open areas where simpler markup is desired, or where a
    content management system controls the markup being output, we recommend applying
    the <code>sage-type</code> class on a container around such content. This
    leads to some default styling applied to the tags within the container
    include our preferred colors and block spacing.
  </p>

  <div class="docs-container">
    <div class="sage-type">
      <div class="sage-type">
        <h3>User-generated content</h3>
        <p>See how content inside this <code>sage-type</code> container automatically recieves corresponding type specs?</p>
      </div>
      <br />
      <div class="sage-code-snippet">
        <pre class="prettyprint"><code>&lt;div class="sage-type"&gt;
      &lt;h3&gt;User-generated content&lt;/h3&gt;
      &lt;p&gt;See how content inside this &lt;code&gt;sage-type&lt;/code&gt; container automatically recieves corresponding type specs?&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

